{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_bellatrix_ver03/data/sn89075140/00516993315/1937092301/0407.xml":{"full_text":"The Tri-County News\nEstablished 1897.\nCatered at the Poetofdce In Grind Rapids, hio, as\nsecond-class matter under Act of March 8,1879\nWALTER W. COWARD-Editor\nGARNETT COWARD-Managing Editor\nof: Northwestern Ohio Publisher\u2019s Association\nNational Editorial Association.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nPer Year_$1.00\nSix Month*-.50\nThree Month*- .25\nPayable in Advance\nADVERTISING RATES\nCauls of Thanks.-50\nReaders, per line-.10\nDisplay Rates furnished\non application.\nIF YOUR HOUSE CATCHES FIRE?\nIf your house catches fire\u2014keep your head. Fol\nlow a simple but vital routine and your chance of es\ncaping safely will be tremendously Increased. Suc\ncumb to panic and thoughtless activity and your next\nsstep may be to the hospital or the morgue.\nWriting in McCall\u2019s, John J. McElligott, New\nYork Fire Chief, points out that two-thirds of pur an\nnual fire deatns occur In dwellings, mainly became the\noccupants don\u2019t know how to get out. And t-.i-v\nfourths of these victi m are trapped on top floors, be\ner, use they fall to re.'og. <zt the danger signals of heat\nend pressure on bedr wm doors.\nThe first thing the householder should do if\nawakened by fire, is to feel the bedroom door panel. If\nthe wood Is hot, don\u2019t open the door unless you want\nto sign your death warrant. If there is an ex t via a\nwindow or riot, take it. If not, stay in the room with\nthe door closed and call for help.\nIf the door Is relatively cool, open it an inch, with\nyour body braced against it so it can be Instantly\nslammed if a rush of hot air follows the opening. If the\nheat outside is bearable, move with the utmost speed.\nDon\u2019t try to save belongings. Fire travels a thousand\ntimes faster than the uninitiated realize. A stairway\nthat is passable one minute, may be a roaring inferno\nthe nea. And once you\u2019re outside\u2014stay out! Many a\nlife has been lost because someone rushed back inside\na burning building.\nChief McElligott recommends that every family\nhold periodic fire drills, especially if there are children.\nThe experience these drills provide may be a life-saver\nif fire eventually breaks out\u2014a min'd and body trained\nin the technique of escaping a burning building, are\nnot so susceptible to the deadly delay and panic.\nPERMANENT PROSPERITY\nMany of the evils from which the country suffers\nshould be abolished without much difficulty. Industrial\ndepressions seem to come in this class, since everybody\nwill shout andArote for permanent prosperity.\nWhen business is poor and employment 'scarce,\nthree causes are mainly to blame: First, excessive\nspeculation. That upset the applecart In 1929. Second\nexcessive debts, which put farmers and home owners\nin a bad hole. Third, bank troubles, which force em\nployers to pay up loans instead of hiring labor.\nTo abolish such misfortunes, the government,\nstates, and cities must avoid borrowing too much mon\ney. Passing the buck to future years simply passes it\nto ourbelves.\nOne of the many reasons why the present business\noutlook is very hopeful, is that caution prevails in\nspeculation and lending money. The financial joy-rid\ners who smashed us up in 1929 are not stepping on\nthe gas much now.\nThe American people built the grandest country\nin the world by, giving an honest day\u2019s work for a\nday\u2019s wage, and by paying their debts. They looked for\nsuccess, not to strokes of luck, but to strong and skil\nful strokes with hammer and hoe, in the shop and on\nthe farm.\nPeople seem to have gone back to work with much\nof this old time energy. They don\u2019t shrink so much\nfrom perspiration and backache. That spirit tamed the\nwilderness in former days, and it is capable of abolish\ning depressions and giving us continuous prosperity.\nSCHOOL OB GANG?\nIf you aak a boy which he would rather have, a\nschoolbook or an automobile, he will probably choose\nthe automobile. After he grows up and feels handi\ncapped by ignoranre, he may wish he had chosen the\nbook.\nWhen the schoolhouse opened its door in Septem\nber, a similar choice is placed before each child. The\nschool offers him the world\u2019s wisdom and experience.\nMeanwhile the street crowd would entice him away to\nthe unruly pleasure of the kid world.\nONE\u2019S ENOUGH\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s present troubles over his\nappointment of Associate Justice Black may be an in\nfluence that will lesson the Chief\u2019s desire to name six\njustices to the Supreme Court.\nYou can\u2019t improve your home town by sitting\naround and telling what someone else pught to do for\nThe president in his speech over the radio the other\nnight, said, \u2018he was doing everything possible to keep\nthis nation out of war.\u201d Sounds like Woodrow Wilson,\nto us.\nMcClure\nMr. and Mrs. John Krohn and\ndaughter Miss Dorothy, spent Sunday\nevening with friends at Holgate.\nMr. and Mrs. H. L. Middleton were\ndinner guests of Mr. and Mrs. Faye\nJones, on Sunday.\nMrs. Mae Bonner of Toledo, was a\nweek-end guest of Mrs. Lizzie Mc\nClure.\nMr. and Mrs. George Fallis and\ndaughter of Toledo spent Sunday at\nthe T. U. McClure home here.\nMrs. Sarah E. Hutcheson visited\nChauncey Conrad and family at Ly\nons, Ohio, Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. F. B. McKenna, of\nDetroit spent the week-end with Mr.\nand Mrs. H. C. Seekamp\nA reception and donation will be\ngiven for Rev. and Mrs. Lyle Loomis,\nFriday evening, at the parsonage.\nEveryone is welcome.\nThere will be no preaching service\nat the M. E. Church here, because of\nthe Homecoming at the Grelton\nchurch. The pastor, Rev. H.W.Stoody\nand Sunday School Superintendent,\nurges all from here to attend the\nhomecoming.\nBond Collins who has been spend\ning the past few months among his\npeople here, left Monday to return\nto his work at Hollywood, Calif.\nLeland Washington returned, at the\nend of the week, from a vacation\nspent in Pennsylvania.\nMrs. Grace Stratton and Miss\nVreeland of Temperance, Mich., spent\nSaturday afternoon with Wm. Ker\natetter and Mrs. Frances Zimmerman.\nAmong those from here who at\ntended the reunion of the McClure\nfamilies at Bowling Green City Park\nwere: T. U. McClure, Mr. and Mrs.\nBryce McClure, Mr. and Mrs. B. El.\nFlier, Mr. and Mrs. Gail McClure,\nand Mr. and Mrs. Don McClure.\nElection of Sunday School officers\nand a rally day service will be held\nSunday, October 3, at the M. E.\nChurch here.\nRev. Strouse, of Holgate filled the\npulpit at St Paul\u2019s Lutheran church\nhere Sunday evening, in the absence\nof Rev. H. F. Hamburger who was\nconducting services at the 50th. an\nniversary celebration of the Malinta\nTrinity Lutheran of which he is pas\ntor.\nA son was bom to Mr. and Mrs.\nRalph Ward Monday, September 20th.\nMrs. Lola Skinner \u00bbmi daughter\nVivian of Toledo spent Sunday with\nMrs. Loie Hockman.\nMrs. H. C. Seekamp visited her\ndaughter Mrs. Dean Daley, who is\nvery ill, at her home at Maumee,\nSaturday.\nMembers of the Friendly class sur\nprised Mrs. Harry Hartman with a\ndinner party, on Sunday, following\nchurch services, the occasion being\nbar birthday. \u25a0The affair was planned\nby her daughter Marie.\nMiss Opal Washington who has\nipv been spending the past few months\nh Illinois has returned to McClum\nRoy Clark was removed to his\nhome here from the Community hos\npital, where his leg had been amputa\nted below the knee.\nFuneral services for Mrs. Sadie\nHale, wife of Fred Hale, were held\nSunday afternoon at the United\nBrethren Church, with Rev. C. R. Ar\ncher of Columbus Grove, officiating\nand Rev. L. Loomis assisting. Inter\nment in the McClure cemetery.\nMr. and Mrs. P E. Teegardin and\nchildren, Leona and Robert, spent\nSunday with relatives in Detroit.\nR. J. Peery is reported as improv\ning from his recent Illness, friends\nwill be glad to learn.\nThe marriage of Miqs Katherine\nGuy Shaffer, and Ivan Johnson of De\ntroit, son of Mr. and Mrs.. W. W.\nShaffer, daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\nJohnson was solemnized Sunday,\nSeptember 19th, at 1:20 o\u2019clock in St.\nPaul\u2019s Lutheran church by the Rev.\nH. F. Hamburger. Miss Marcella\nGood and Robert Hull of Detroit,\nwere the only attendanta The bride\nwore a costume of royal blue velvet\nwith hat and accessories to match\nand Miss Good was attired in an en\nsemble of rust colored crepe and\nmatching accessories. The groom and\nbest man wore dark blue suits. A\ndinner and reception was held, follow\ning the ceremony, at the home of the\nbride with only the immediate fam\nilies present, after which the couple\nleft for a short eastern trip and Nia\ngara Falls. After their return they\nwill reside in Detroit where Mr. John\nson has purchased a home.\nMilton Center\nMr. and Mrs. Ortez Galligher and\ndaughter Rose Ann spent Saturday\nevening with Mr. and Mrs. M. V.\nHathaway and children. All enjoyed a\nfish fry, it being the birthday of Mrs.\nHathaway.\nMr. and Mrs. Ham Hathaway spent\nSunday with Mr. and Mrs. Reed\nHathaway at Deshier. In the after\nnoon Mr. and Mrs. Harry Lingo of\nToledo called.\nMr. and Mrs. J. W. .Hathaway-left\nlast week on their vacation.\nMr. and Mrs. Newell Fifer of Tole\ndo were the guests of Mr. and Mrs. J.\nW. Hathaway and Mr. and Mrs. M. V.\nHathaway, Sunday.\nThis community was sorry to heal\nof the death of Mr. Thomas Davis.\nV. S. Morehouse and wife spent\nSunday with S. B. Morehouse and\nwife. E. S. Burson was a caller in the\nsame home in the evening.\nMiss Helen Hanawalt of Defiance\ncalled on Mrs. M. L. Norton, Saturday\nafternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Harold Norton and\nson Richard of Cleveland were guests\nof the former\u2019s mother, Mrs. M. L.\nNorton last Tuesday and Wednesday,\nreturning to their home Thursday.\nRichard remained and drove his grand\nmother to Detroit returning, Satur\nday. Richard returned to his home in\nCincinnati, Saturday night.\nMr. and Mrs. Ralph Norton and son\nEdward spent Sunday with Mrs. M.\nL. Norton.\nCallers at the E. S. Burson home\nlast week were, Mrs. Alice Corfman\nHarmon, of Mansfield, Ohio, an old\nschoolmate of Mrs.- Burson; Mrs.\nOlivia Baumgardner, of Weston, a\nsister of Mr. Burson, V. S. Morehouse.\nMr. and Mrs. Ray Bowman of Por\ntage spent Sunday evening with their\ndaughter and family, Mr. and Mrs.\nArchie Dilsaver and son, Junior.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Martens and\nLois, Mr. and Mrs. Roy Smith, Eileen\nand Carl of Toledo were Sunday\nguests at the Henry Martens home.\nMrs. Louis Haas and Alta were\nFriday afternoon callers of Mrs. Carl\nMartins and Lois.\nMrs. Harry Mann spent Tuesday\nin Bowling Green.\nMisses Zoe and Irene Fawley spent\nthe week-end with their parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. S. A. Fawley, of near Mc\nClure.\nMF. Carl Shaffer spent the week\nend in Bowling Green.\nMrs. Earl Tolies, of Weston spent\nlast Thursday with Mr. and Mrs. C.\nE. Trumbull.\nMr. and Mrs. Emmett Trumbull\nspent,- last. Wednesday- evening In\nClubs\nSocial Societies\nMBS. LAMSON ENTERTAINS\nBLUE BELL GARDEN CLUB\nMrs. Lillian Lamon was hostess to\nthe Blue Belle Garden Club in her\nbeautiful country home on Thursday\nafternoon. \"Shadow Patterns\u201d was\nthe topic for the day and \u2018My Favor*\nite Tree\u201d was the roll call. The fol\nlowing interesting program was giv\nen; papers: \u201cTribute To Trees,\" Mrs.\nIda Barr; \"Natures Largest Plant,\u201d\nMrs. Orpha Sheets; \u201cThe Torry Pine,\u201d\nMrs. Janet Johnston; and \"Weeping\nTrees,\u201d Mrs. Alice Box. Mrs. Marion\nManor rendered two beautiful piano\nselections. Mrs. Janet Johnston will\nentertain the club in October.\nThe Sophomore, Junior and Senior\nclasses enjoyed a weiner roast and\npicnic at the Providence Metropolitan\nPark on Friday evening. The evening\nwas spent in singing around the\ncampfire, and a scavanger hunt and a\ngood time was reported by all who\nattended\nENTERTAINED\nFIDELIS CLASS\nMrs. Ronald Rager entertained the\nFidelia class of the Presbyterian\nChurch in her home on Friday after\nnoon. During the business meeting a\nbake sale was planned for Oct. 9, at\nKaton\u2019s grocery. At the close of the\nafternoon delicious refreshments were\nserved to: Mesdames Marion Manor,\nWeston.\nMr. and Mrs. George Bradshaw\nwere Sunday dinner guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. Eugene Challen and family\nand in the afternoon called on Mrs.\nLottie Saylor and Roy Edwards.\nMrs. Robert Rosenberger and Mr.\nAndy Rosenberger visited Mr. Edw.\nWoody and Mr. and Mrs. Kenneth\nWoody of Delta, Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Don Woody of Liberty\nCenter called on Mrs. Robert Rosen\nberger Thursday evening.\nPottertown\nHarman Hartman called on James\nErrett, Friday.\nRay Potter called on his mother,\nMrs. John Wright Sunday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Irven Morehouse and\nchildren called at the A. L. Bassett\nhome Thursday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. James Errett were\nWednesday guests of Mr and Mrs.\nMerl Shepard of near McClure.\nMrs. Edward Beard and Mrs. Van\nEuler of Liberty Center called at the\nPhillips home Saturday afternoon.\nMrs. Ray Potter, of near Weston\nspent Sunday evening with Mr. and\nMrs. Glenn Potter and Martha.\nMr. and Mrs. Wm. Jimison, of Has\nkins, were Wednesday afternoon call\ners at the John Wright home.\nMr. and Mrs. James Phillips, Rob\nert and Delmar spent Sunday after\nnoon with friends at Liberty Center.\nMr. and Mrs. E. A. Frost and Mr.\nand Mrs. James Frost of Whitehouse\nwere Sunday dinner gueats of Mr. and\nMrs. C. E. Frost and children.\nMrs. Alva Courtney and sons, and\nMrs. Bassett called on Mrs. Carl Clay\nand children and Mrs. Emil Bryan of\nWeston Saturday afternoon.\nMrs. Wm .Russell assisted Mrs.\nArza Wright cook for silo fillers Mon\nday and Tuesday.\nMrs. Alva Courtney and sons were\nMcClure visitors Thursday morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard Davis in com\npany with Mr. and Mrs. Cart Strong\nof Grand Rapids are touring the\nEastern States.\nMrs. Anna Dennis and Mrs. Harvey\nDennis of Liberty township and Mrs.\nBassett helped cook for silo fillers at\nthe Courtney home, Wednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Lawrence Potter\ncalled on Mrs. Minnie Junkins Friday.\nMrs. James Donald and Mrs.' Bert\nBlackburn of Weston were also\nguests in the same home.\nWord has been received here at the\nbirth of a 7 3-4 lb. boy to Mr. and\nMrs. E. J. Fisher of St. Louis, Mich,\nFriday morning. Mrs. Fisher was for\nmerly Miss Dorothy Bassett, daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs. A. L. Bassett\nMr. and Mrs. Harry Barber of Ru\ndolph were Sunday dinner guests at\nher sister, Mrs. Alva Courtney and\nHelen Thurston, Ruby Smith, Flossie j\nKeister, Loal Armbruater, Clara Cros\nby, Jennie Warner, Helen Moyer, Ed\nna Box, Stella Katon, Helen Heyman,\nEsther Vollmar, Dorothy Snyder;\nguests, Mrs. Flora' Katon, Mrs. At\nlanta Box, Mrs. Alta Hutchinson,\nMrs. Winfred Gallagher, by the com\nmittee, Mrs. AUce Box, Mrs. Clara\nGuyer, and Mrs. Rager.\nPLUS ULTRA CLASS\nMrs. Pearl Gill was hostess to the\nPlus Ultra Class in her home ~on\nThursday evening Mrs. Lillian Lam\nson gave impressive devotionals.\nCharades were played following the\nthe business meeting after which de\nlicious refreshments were served to\na large attendance and Rev. and Mrs.\nJ. W. Meyers of Haskins, who were\nguests. Mrs. Pearl Long, Mrs. Myrta\nLong, and Mrs. Cora Sherwood assist\ned Mrs. Gill in entertaining.\nP. T. A. MEETS NEXT\nWEDNESDAY EVENING\nThe regular meeting of the P. T. A.\nI will be held in the school auditorium\nnext Wednesday evening. A good at\ntendance is desired.\nThe Stella Club of the O. E S. will\nhold a bake and produce sale in the\ndisplay room of the Toledo Edison\nCo., on Saturday, Sept 25.\nfamily. Mr. and Mrs. Stanley Straus\nbaugh and son Jimmy of Bloomdale\ncalled in the afternoon.\nMrs. John Tanner and Irene and\nMiss Anna Sherman of Liberty Cen\nter spent Tuesday evening with the\nPhillips family.\nMr. and Mrs. Kenneth Golden and\nPhyllis, Mr. and Mrs. Francis Mc\nPheron, Bobby and Francis, Jr., of\nNewport, Mich., and Mrs. Grace Gol\nden of Lima called at the Lawrence\nPotter home, Sunday.\nSunday dinner guests at the A. L.'\nBassett home were, Mr. and Mrs.\nRobert Adams, of Toledo, Mr. and\nMrs. Irven Morehouse and children of\nCustar. Supper guests were Mr. and\nMrs. Carl Clay and children of Wes\nton and their house guest, Mrs. John!\nThompson, of Logan. I\nStorage supplies of all dairy pro\nducts were running 15 per cent above\naverage on* August 1.\nOhio people who are Interested In\nhaving short courses established at\nOhio State University, should write to\nJunior Dean L. E. Jackson, college of\nagriculture. The courses would cover\nagricultural subjects, be given during\nthe winter and early spring, and\nwould provide an educational oppor\ntunity for those who cannot enroll in\nregular courses.\nBeekeepers are interested in trials\nof a new strain of red lover which\nfurnishes more pasture for bees than\nthe ordinary kinds. First trials show\ned that the new kind has shorter cor\nolla tubes which permit bees to reach\nnectar in the bottom of the tubes bet\nter than in the old varieties.\nEntries of dairy cattle in the Na\ntional Dairy Show to be held at Col\numbus, October 9 to 16, indicate there\nwill be at least 1,000 head of the\ncountry\u2019s best specimens on exhibit\nwhen the gates open.\nn MOM WAS LOST\nFor want of a few hundred dollars many\ngolden opportunities are lost... crjdit\nis lost... personal possessions are lost\nand often good health is lost\nThe City Loan is your assurance of\nready cash to prevent losses, to provide\nfor the things you need to buy, to keep\nyou from getting behind in your pay*\nments, to enable you to drive bargains,\ncontrol financial difficulties.\nTell us how much you need up to\n$1000. We will arrange the rest for you\nas you wish... on the best of term\u00bb\nA. L. SLOAN, Mgr.,\n124 W. Wooster Street\nBOWLING GREEN, O.\nPersayus\u00a3 ^financuiq rZ'ytoftOOO\nOur Leaders!\nOFFER YOU\nCOMBINATION No. 50-tt\nTHIS NEWS